title: [Pre-si  Post-Si] Verify BIOS to pCode mailbox commands support
description:
Test Purpose/Description:

Need to make sure we support all the commands between BIOS and PCODE specified in the attached document.


Command namenbsp; Command indexnbsp; Drop available in

SET_UPI_FREQnbsp; 136nbsp; 0p5a

SET_RLINK_FREQnbsp; 199nbsp; 0p5a

MULTI_SKT_UPDnbsp; 197nbsp; 0p3


After discussed with bios owner, got some information:


For command SET_UPI_FREQ, there will be an option Intel(R) UPI Link Frequency, we can check the command by changing the frequency to other value, then check after save and reset.

For command SET_RLINK_FREQ, this option will be dropped, no need to test.

For command MULTI_SKT_UPD, the bios code is not ready, when ready, we assume there will be an option under bios setup for multi_skt_upd, triger multi-die interconnecte training, if we dont trigger this, there will be 1 die work, the CPU cores number will decrease, if trigger, there will be 2 die
or more 4 dies work, the CPU number will increase.


Prerequisites:

N/A


H/W Requirement:

ITP Tool


SW and Tools Required:

PythonSv / Cscript tool


Spec Reference:

PRD


Special notes and BKM:

None

title: [Pre-Si] Check if CHA SAD Decode for CXL Interleave Schemes and Target ID Decode correctly.
description:
Test Purpose/Description:

This case is to verify the CHA SAD Decode for IAL Interleave Schemes and Target ID Decode can changes the related registers correctly.

In this case, Memory_Info_Valid, Memory_Active, Mem_Enable, Memory_Size_High and Memory_Size_Low will be checked.


Pre Requisite:

None.


HW Required:

1. On Pre-silicon;:
Eagle Stream Simics environment (Recommend configuration: CPU with IAL Devices)

$ial_enabled=TRUE
$ial_ganged_topology = [1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0]
$ial_device_serial_number = [0x1234567890000000, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0]
$ial_io_enable = [TRUE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE]
$ial_cache_enable = [TRUE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE]
$ial_mem_enable = [TRUE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE]
$ial_mem_hdm_count = [0x2, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0]
$ial_mem_size_mb_range1 = [256, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0]
$ial_mem_media_type_range1 = [0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0]
$ial_mem_desired_interleave_range1 = [0x001, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0]
$ial_mem_size_mb_range2 = [256, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0]
$ial_mem_media_type_range2 = [0x1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0]
$ial_mem_desired_interleave_range2 = [0x0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0]
$ial_ports_for_links = ["1a", "", "", "", "", ""]
SW and Tools Required:

Simics.
BHS-pre-Silicon:

BHS CXL wiki: https://wiki.ith.intel.com/display/ITSFID/GNR+CXL+POR+Config+Settings
Spec Reference:

Intel® Flex Bus and Intel Accelerator Link 7.1

Special Notes and BKM:

Memory decode library flow for IAL accelerator in UEFI FW shall preform the steps below: 

1.      When Memory_Info_Valid and Memory_Active are 1 in thenbsp; DVSEC memory size register mapped in configuration space, read Memory_Size_High and Memory_Size_Low fields for each HDM range from the same register.

2.      Compute the size of the HDM range and map the range in system address space. Mapping HDMnbsp; requires 1 general purpose DRAM rule for every memory size range requested by the accelerator andnbsp; 1 remote DRAM rule per 
remote socket.

3.      Program Memory_Base_Low and Memory_Base_High for each HDM range in thenbsp; DVSEC memory base register mapped in configuration space.

4.      Set Intel Mem_Enable in the DVSEC control register to enable memory access protocol that supports device attached memory. This shall ensure any subsequent accesses to HDM are decoded and routed to the local memory 
by the device.  

check point: offset 0x00, 0x04, 0x0C, 0x18, 0x1C, 0x28, 0x2C


Notes:

Due to the serialDebugMsgLvl change(from 0023.D.52), the default minimum level only print limited logs as shown below:

1. Platform CXL table

2. Platform DIMM table

3. SAD/Route table; TAD rule 

4. Clustering mode 

If the TCD test string cannot be found in the serial logs, pls change serialDebugMsgLvl to Normal(0x2)

EDKII Menu -> Platform Configuration -> Miscellaneous Configuration -> Serial Debug Message Level -> Normal

title: [ACM] [ACM Negative Test] TC.CError.11 Enable BTG profile 5 and verify no success boot - BTG_P5, TXT_DIS, TPM2.0, Corrupted IBB, Tboot
description:
Test Purpose/Description:

[ACM] [ACM Negative Test] TC.CError.11 Enable BTG profile 5 and verify no success boot - BTG_P5, TXT_DIS, TPM2.0, Corrupted IBB, Tboot

Required Setup Options:

NA

 

Pre Requisite: 

spsFITc.exe or fitm.exe

 

H/W Requirement:

SF600 or Fitm.exe


S/W and Tools Requirement:

NA


Test Steps:


Steps

Description

Expected Result

Step 1
Open BIOS image with spsFITc.exe or Fitm.exe

@EB

No issue.

Step 2

Set following options:

Boot Guard Configuration -> Boot Profile: Boot Guard Profile 5 - FVME

TXT Configuration -> TXT Supported: Enabled 

@EB

No issue.

Step 3
Build it and output outimage.bin

@EB

No issue.

Step 4
Open outimage.bin with HxD Hex Editor

@EB

No issue.

Step 5
Search“__IBBS__ “ and  the first “__IBBS__ “ near by"__ACBP__", it's 8 bytes. Find the next  68th byte, corrupt any value of the next 32 bytes(From the 68th byte). Save the image as outimage_1.bin.

@EB

No issue.

Step 6

Flash outimage_1.bin on SUT.

@EB

Image flash successfully.

Step 7

Power on SUT.

@EB

SUT can't boot up.

For EGS：
SUT should shutdown,  power state change from S0 to S5 immediately, postcode would be 0.2.

For BHS：

we only expect the core to be down, platform will be up, it is expected anchor cove shutdown is basically a sleep state in core, so you would see platform will be up and it will look like hang, you can't see a reboot


postcode would be 10 and open pythonsv run:

unlock()

sv.refresh()
import core.debug as cd

cd.core_live_status()

It will return:

| Next ROB label | distributed_status_cr0_dirty_bit_check | U0000      |

title: [Post Si] Memory Read UCE on Mirror and Non-Mirror Region
description:
Test Purpose / Description :
Partial mirroring memory addresses across two DDR channels. Also the mirroring is not handled by IMC but M2M. It means there could be one set of addresses that are mirrored
and another set of addresses in the same IMC that are not mirrored.
Inject uncorrected error within non-mirroring address region.

HW required :
All DIMM were same DIMM types. ITP

Pre-Requisites :
For mirroring, at least two DDR channels must be populated in each IMC.

SW and tools :
Pre-installed OS on SUT(P1 Windows) , Cscript

title: To Verify  _PSD ACPI methods for P-states
description:
Test case Purpose/ Description: 

To verify "_PSD " ACPI method implementation for P States in 10nm programs.


Pre-Requisite: 

Pre-installed WinOS Drive needs to be connected to the SUT


H/W Requirement:

 None


S/W and Tools requirement:

System Scope tool


Spec Reference: None


Special notes and BKM: 

ICXD Updated based on Bug-ID: 1607248682 as a reference
pre_condition:
1. For alternative ACPI dump option download tool from below path take latest build.  

https://www.acpica.org/downloads/binary-tools


2. As per ACPI spec only with minimum 2 sockets PSD is generated. And got confirmation by running on ICX 1S platform(used ACPICA tool), couldn’t see PSD info in ACPICA dump.


As per ACPI spec version-6.3

Num Processors Integer (DWORD) - The number of processors belonging to the domain for this logical processor’s P-states. OSPM will not start performing power state transitions to a particular P-state until this number of processors belonging to the same domain have been detected and started


Example This is an example usage of the _PSD structure in a Processor structure in the namespace. The example represents a two processor configuration with three performance states per processor. For all performance states, there exists dependence between the two processors, such that one processor transitioning to a particular performance state, causes the other processor to transition to the same performance state. OSPM will be required to coordinate the P-state transitions between the two processors and can initiate a transition on either processor to cause both to transition to the common target P-state.

title: [BOOT GUARD] Verify system behavior when Boot Guard Profile is set to 3
description:
Test Purpose:

Boot Guard performs BIOS Initial Boot Block verification, but no measurement.

If verification fails, BTG will not handoff to BIOS for execution, and in-band recover will not be possible and the IBB must be recovered out of band.


Setup Options Required:

Use utility to program enforcement policies in ME ROM region

Set enforcement policy to profile 3

Rebuild IFWI image for test, named it as IFWI_Profile3.bin

How to customize BTG Profile:

1. Know SPS FW version and get corresponding version spsFITc.exe or Fitm.exe.

2. Open spsFITc.exe or Fitm.exe and load SPS based IFWI.

3. Go to Configuration, Boot Guard Configuration.

Set OEM Public Key Hash to AF69F62499DF4234265A43E9FABE6A34A3034DA4CB3F9FADF95CA685BFE7683C
For SPR and GNR, it  should be:
F8F0E369158176990A549ED4C36D1A8639D8873DEFF7ED2DE34CB41BCCB30476CE0AA063BC5B7AACFFD9509E9640C699

Set Key Manifest ID to 1

Set Boot Guard Profile Configuration to desired profile.

4. Go to Configuration, Manufacturing Flow, End Of Manufacturing, set Status to EOM on Heci command.

5. Build IFWI with these setting and get outimage.bin.


BIOS Region: 0x01300000~0x01FFFFFF.

Start address of IBB data region is 0x1300000 + 0xCE0000=0X1FE0000

Start address of IBB hash region is:

1. Open IFWI_Profile0.bin, search __IBBS__, get the address, such as 0x01ff6890h

2. Find hash region based on above address + offset 0x60h.


HW Config and Binary Mapping:

HW Cfg: any Binary: CRB


HW Required:

None


SW and Tools Required:

BootGuardInfo tool is ready.(Note: New tool TxtBtgInfo should be used after confirm working, tool owner: Bekefi, Stephen C)

TXTBtginfo.efin -c a -a


BootGuardInfo tool is ready.

TPM 2.0 module is connected and enabled in BIOS setup. Note: TPM module has been properly provisioned before test start. ( Eg. Tpm2DefaultTxtProv.nsh SHA256 Example )

For PreSi : In Simics: Need to set below variables in run script, must run with Simics WB.

$boot_guard_enable = TRUE

$txt_enable = TRUE

$tpm_enable = TRUE

$tpm_version = 2.0

$tpm_location= 1


PRD Covered:

1404540077- TXT/BtG - BIOS to support Boot guard

1404540886- TXT/BtG - SEC Phase updates to support Boot Guard ACM

1404540893- TXT/BtG - Bios must disable Protect Bios Environment Timer (SPBET) before AP initialization

 Expected Result

Open BIOS image with spsFITc.exe or Fitm.exe

Set OEM public key as AF69F62499DF4234265A43E9FABE6A34A3034DA4CB3F9FADF95CA685BFE7683C, set Key Manifest ID as 1.

F8F0E369158176990A549ED4C36D1A8639D8873DEFF7ED2DE34CB41BCCB30476CE0AA063BC5B7AACFFD9509E9640C699

title: [Post Si] PCIe Gen4 Leaky Bucket runtime handling
description:
The UEFI FW setup menu shall provide _LeakyBucketSetupOptions for each IIO root port.When the system POSTs, the UEFI FW shall program the Gen4 leaky bucket registers LEKBERR, LEKBERR0, LEKBERR1, and LEKBAR for each IIO root port by setting their fields equal to the values of the corresponding _LeakyBucketSetupOptions.

SKX-SP added PCIe gen3 threshold based corrected error reporting. Customers were required to implement a FW/SW solution to filter out normally occurring errors. ICX-SP's PCIe Gen4 based Leaky bucket capability is a HW implementation to simplify FW/SW implementation. 

ICX-SP has enhanced PCIe Gen4 corrected error handling by adding Leaky Bucket capability. This would allow filtering out normally occurring errors as determined by acceptable link BER (Bit Error Ratio). UEFI FW is expected to initialize various registers to program the logic appropriately. During run-time, UEFI FW is expected to initiate link re-training should a 'prolonged error event' is detected. Optionally, UEFI FW may require to update the initial settings during run-time should the link degrade

LeakyBucketSetupOptions: Setup options corresponding to register fields as shown in the following table (one instance of the table for each root port):

Setup Option

Field

Register(s)

Expected BER

EXP_BER

LEKBERR0, LEKBERR1

Error Burst Protection Time Window (Gen1/2)

AGGRERR

LEKBERR

Error Burst Protection Time Window (Gen3/4)

G3AGGRERR

LEKBERR1

Error Threshold (Gen1/2)

ERRTHRESH

LEKBERR

Error Threshold (Gen3/4)

G3ERRTHRESH

LEKBERR

Trigger Enable - Gen3/4 Re-Equalization

G3LBEEN

LEKBERR

Trigger Enable - Gen2 Link Degradation

LBEG2DEGRADEEN

LEKBAR

Trigger Enable - Gen3 Link Degradation

LBEG3DEGRADEEN

LEKBAR

Trigger Enable - Gen4 Link Degradation

LBEG4DEGRADEEN

LEKBAR

title: [TPM][PSS  Post-Si]TPM2.0 Configuration and settings
description:
Test Steps:

 
Stepactionexpected_resultsnotes
Step 1Burn the correct image to target board and connect a serial cable to host machine for saving logs.No error occurred
Step 2Power on target board and press F2 to boot to BIOS Menu Setup Interface.The system successfully boots to  BIOS Menu Setup Interface
Step 3Enter EDKII Menu > TCG2 Configuration menu.
Check"Current TPM Device Interface"		Should be "TIS" or "PTP FIFO"
Step 4Enter EDKII Menu > TCG2 Configuration menu.
Set Attempt Rev of TPM2 ACPI Table to a different value with Current Rev of TPM2 ACPI Table. (Rev 4 to Rev 3 and then Rev 3 to Rev 4)
Press F10 to save changes and then reset.		SUT reset success.
No PPI request need user confirmation. Current Rev of TPM2 ACPI Table should change to Attempt Rev of TPM2 ACPI Table
Step 5Enter EDKII Menu > TCG2 Configuration menu.
Set Attempt PPI Version to a different value with Current PPI Version. (1.3 to 1.2 and then 1.2 to 1.3)
Press F10 to save changes and then reset.		SUT reset success.
No PPI request need user confirmation. Current Rev of TPM2 ACPI Table should change to Attempt PPI Version.
Step 6Enter EDKII -> TCG2 Configuration Menu. Check PCR Bank: only SHA256(EGS) is selected. GNR(SHA1/SHA256/SHA384) all checked . Check "TPM Operation" default value is "<No Action>".No error.
Step 7Enter EDKII Menu > TCG2 Configuration menu.
set "TPM Operation" value to <TPM2 HierarchyControl(TPM_RH_OWNER YES, TPM_RH_ENDORSEMENT YES)>.
Press F10 to save changes and then reset

SUT reset success. No PPI request need user confirmation.

"TPM Operation" is back to default <No Action>.


Step 8Enter EDKII Menu > TCG2 Configuration menu.
Set "TPM Operation" value to <TPM2 HierarchyControl(TPM_RH_OWNER NO, TPM_RH_ENDORSEMENT NO)>.
Press F10 to save and exit to setup and reboot.

SUT reset success. No PPI request need user confirmation.

"TPM Operation" is back to default <No Action>.


Step 9Enter EDKII Menu > TCG2 Configuration menu.
Set "TPM Operation" value to <TPM2 HierarchyControl(TPM_RH_OWNER NO, TPM_RH_ENDORSEMENT YES)>.
Press F10 to save changes and then reset.

SUT reset success. No PPI request need user confirmation.

"TPM Operation" is back to default <No Action>.


Step 10Execute the command in internal shell
dmpstore -b -all Tcg2PhysicalPresenceFlags		Sample:
dmpstore -b -all Tcg2PhysicalPresenceFlags
00000000: E2 00 07 00
If E2 is shown, there will be a physical presence.
If E0 is shown, there will be no physical presence. Device can boot without any confirm dialog and ignore Step 12
Step 11Enter EDKII Menu > TCG2 Configuration menu.
Set "TPM Operation" value to "TPM ClearControl(NO)+Clear".
 Press F10 to save changes and then reset.		A confirm dialog as below prompted and     SUT boot passed after pressing F12:
A configuration change was requested to clear this computer's TPM (Trusted Platform Module)
WARNING: Clearing erases information stored on the TPM. You will lose all created keys and access to data encrypted by these keys.
Press F12 to clear the TPM
Press ESC to reject this change request and continue

If E0 is shown, there will be no physical presence.
Device can boot without any confirm dialog and ignore Step 12
Step 12Press F12 to accept changes.SUT boot success after clear TPM
Step 13Enter EDKII Menu > TCG2 Configuration menu. Set "TPM Operation" value to  <TCG2 LogAllDigests>.
Press F10 to save changes and then reset.		SUT reset to bios setup and no PPI request need user confirmation.
Enter EDKII Menu > TCG2 Configuration menu.
Check PCR bank: All PCR Bank is selected.

EGS: All PCR Bank is selected except SHA1 .(EGS doesn't support SHA1)
Step 14Enter EDKII Menu > TCG2 Configuration menu > TPM Operation
Choose <TPM2 PCR_Allocate(Algorithm IDs)> and set "TPM2 Operation Parameter" [0]
Press F10 to save and exit to setup and reboot.

TPM Parameters:
[0]: No PCR Bank
[1]: SHA1
[2]: SHA256
[4]: SHA384
[10]: SM3_256		A confirm dialog as below prompted:
A configuration change was requested to change the boot measurements to use PCR bank(s) of this computer's TPM (Trusted Platform Module)
WARNING: Changing the PCR bank(s) of the boot measurements may prevent the Operating System from properly processing the measurements. Please check if your Operating System supports the new PCR bank(s).
WARNING: Secrets in the TPM that are bound to the boot state of your machine may become unusable.

Current PCRBanks is 0x3. (SHA1, SHA256)
New PCRBanks is 0x0. ()

Press F12 to change the boot measurements to use PCR bank(s) of the TPM
Press ESC to reject this change request and continue.
Step 15Press F12 to accept changes.SUT boots to setup success,
Enter EDKII Menu > TCG2 Configuration menu.
Check PCR bank: Change not be saved
TPM does not support PCR bank 0 to be allocated.
Step 16Enter EDKII Menu > TCG2 Configuration menu >     TPM Operation
Choose <TPM2 PCR_Allocate(Algorithm IDs)> and set "TPM2 Operation Parameter"
Change the parameter to select different algorithms.
Press F10 to save changes and then reset.
Press F12 to accept changes.
Everytime after changing the parameters, reboot to EDKII Menu and check the PCR banks status.

Reboot times depends on the number of supported algorithms.
Enter EDKII Menu > TCG2 Configuration menu.
Check PCR bank status: the selected PCR banks should be expected as the parameter.

For example, for FHF:
Change the parameter to 0 to unselect all PCR banks.
Reboot check change not saved, TPM does not support PCR bank 0 to be allocated.

Change the parameter to 4 to only select SHA384.
Reboot check only SHA384 banks is selected.

Change the parameter to 2 to only select SHA256.
Reboot check only SHA 256 banks is selected.

Change the parameter to 6 to select both SHA256 and SHA384.
Reboot and check both SHA256 and SHA384 selected.

(EGS doesn't support SHA1)
Step 17Enter EDKII Menu > TCG2 Configuration menu > Active PCR Banks
Select different combination of PCR banks.
Press F10 to save changes and then reset.
Press F12 to accept changes.
Everytime after changing the PCR banks status, reboot to EDKII Menu and check the PCR banks status.

Reboot times depends on the number of supported algorithms.		Enter EDKII Menu > TCG2 Configuration menu.
Check PCR bank selected status.

For example, for FHF:
If unselect all PCR banks.
Reboot check change not saved, TPM does not support PCR bank 0 to be allocated.

If only select SHA384 PCR bank.
Reboot check only SHA384 banks is selected.

If only select SHA256 PCR bank.
Reboot check only SHA 256 banks is selected.

If select both SHA256 and SHA384.
Reboot and check both SHA256 and SHA384 selected.

(EGS doesn't support SHA1)
Step 18If run this case on EGS/FHF, Set serial debug message level to "Normal" in below knob:
Platform Configuration -> Miscellaneous Configuration ->Serial Debug Message Level = <Normal>

Enter EDKII Menu > TCG2 Configuration menu.
Set "TPM Operation" value to <TPM2 ChangeEPS>.
Press F10 to save changes and then reset.		A confirm dialog as below prompted:
A configuration change was requested to clear and change identity of this computer's TPM (Trusted Platform Module)
WARNING: Clearing erases information stored on the TPM. You will lose all created keys and access to data encrypted with these keys.
WARNING: Changing the identity of the TPM may require additional steps to establish trust into the new identity.
Press F12 to clear and change identity of the TPM
Press ESC to reject this change request and continue
Step 19Press F12 to accept changes.
Check Serial log and there should have below information:
Tpm2ChangeEPS - Success


Test Purpose:

Verify all configuration and settings in TPM2.0 functionality and check whether it works well.

SNR:
First prepare binary for TPM test:
Change binary via spsFIT tool
Go into "PCH Straps by order" -> "PCH Strap 56" and change value of "SS56 Intel DCI" to "disabled"
Then go into "Configuration" -> "Platform Security" -> "Boot Guard Configuration" and change value of "CPU Debugging" to "disabled"
Lastly go into "Configuration" -> "Platform Security" -> "OEM Data" and change value of "OEM Authorized Debug" to "disabled" if it isn't already

Setup Options Required:

1. EDKII -> TCG2 Configuration Menu


HW Required:

1. Whitley ICX

2. TPM2.0 Module

﻿﻿

HW Configuration:

1. dTPM2.0 device interface should be TIS, fTPM2.0 device interface should be PTP CRB

2. Check boot log, if find TPM2.0: dtpm Enabled then current TPM2.0 device is dtpm2.0.

3. Check boot log, if find TPM2.0: ftpm Enabled then current TPM2.0 device is ftpm2.0

4. When set Jumper J6C14 to 2-3, PTT Supported should be grayed out and current TPM2.0 device should be dTPM2.0. 

5. For PTT related, please set J6C14 to 1-2 or remove the jumper on J6C14. Also, in order to avoid loss the jumper, it can be plugged in one pin of the J6C14


SW and Tools Required:

N/A


Expected behaviour:

All configurations and settings can work well.

title: [ACM] [ACM Negative Test] TC.CError.6 Enable BTG profile 5 and verify no success boot - BTG_P5, TXT_DIS, TPM2.0, No KM
description:
Test Purpose/Description:

[ACM] [ACM Negative Test] TC.CError.6 Enable BTG profile 5 and verify no success boot - BTG_P5, TXT_DIS, TPM2.0, No KM

Required Setup Options:

NA

 

Pre Requisite: 

spsFITc.exe or Fitm.exe

 

H/W Requirement:

SF600 or EM100


S/W and Tools Requirement:

NA


Test Steps:


Steps

Description

Expected Result

Step 1
Open BIOS image with spsFITc.exe or Fitm.exe

@EB

No issue.

Step 2

Set following options:

Boot Guard Configuration -> Boot Profile: Boot Guard Profile 5 - FVME

TXT Configuration -> TXT Supported: Enabled 

@EB

No issue.

Step 3
Build it and output outimage.bin

@EB

No issue.

Step 4
Open outimage.bin with HxD Hex Editor

@EB

No issue.

Step 5
Search "_FIT_", change Type 0B to FF. Save it as outimage_1.bin.

@EB

No issue.

Step 6

Flash outimage_1.bin on SUT.

@EB

Image flash successfully.

Step 7

Power on SUT.

@EB

SUT can't boot up.

For EGS：
SUT should shutdown,  power state change from S0 to S5 immediately, postcode would be 0.2.

For BHS：

we only expect the core to be down, platform will be up, it is expected anchor cove shutdown is basically a sleep state in core, so you would see platform will be up and it will look like hang, you can't see a reboot


postcode would be 10 and open pythonsv run:

unlock()

sv.refresh()
import core.debug as cd

cd.core_live_status()

It will return:

| Next ROB label | distributed_status_cr0_dirty_bit_check | U0000      |

title: [ACM] [ACM Function Test] TC.RTM.8.Tboot-Enable BTG profile P4 and verify SRTV - BTG_P4, TXT_EN, NO_TPM, TBoot on Redhat
description:
Test Purpose/Description:

[ACM] [ACM Function Test] TC.RTM.8.Tboot-Enable BTG profile P4 and verify SRTV - BTG_P4, TXT_EN, NO_TPM, TBoot on Redhat

Required Setup Options:

NA

 

Pre Requisite: 

spsFITc.exe or Fitm.exe

 

H/W Requirement:

SF600 or EM100

 

S/W and Tools Requirement:

Tpm2_Cbnt_Prov.nsh

Tpm2PoProv.nsh

getsec.efi

TxtBtgInfo.efi

 

Test Steps:


Steps

Description

Expected Result

Step 1

Platform 

Whitley: Move Jumper J5C5 1-2 to 2-3

Cedarlsland: Connect Jumper J5D2 1-2

EGS: Connect Jumper J5E1 1-2

GNR AP: Connect Jumper J1B8 to 1-2

GNR SP: Connect Jumper J107 to 2-3

SRF SP: Connect Jumper J107 to 2-3

@EB

No issue.

Step 2
Open BIOS image with spsFITc.exe or Fitm.exe

@EB

No issue.

Step 3

Set following options:

Boot Guard Configuration-> Boot Profile: Boot Guard Profile 4 - FVE

TXT Configuration-> TXT Supported: Enabled


 

@EB

No issue.

Step 4
Build it and output outimage.bin

@EB

No issue.

Step 5
Flash outimage.bin on SUT.

@EB

No issue.

Step 6

Boot to BIOS setup.

@EB

No issue.

Step 7

Check NO TPM module

Go to EDKII Menu

@EB

EDKII -> should can't find TCG2 Configuration


Step 8

Enable TXT settings.

EDKII Menu -> Socket Configuration -> Processor Configuration -> Enable SMX <Enable>、VMX <Enable>、Enable Intel(R) TXT <Enable>、MSR Lock Control <Enable>

EDKII Menu -> Socket Configuration -> IIO Configuration -> Intel VT for Directed I/O (VT-d) -> Intel (R) VT for Directed I/O (VT-d) <Yes>

Special Notes for GNR, DMA protection and IOMMU programming should be disabled:

EDK II Menu > Socket configuration > IIO Configuration >  Intel@ VT for Directed I/O (VT-d) >  DMA Control Opt-In Flag  <Disable>

EDK II Menu > Socket configuration > IIO Configuration >

Intel@ VT for Directed I/O (VT-d) > Pre-boot DMA Protection <Disable>

Press F10 to save.

@EB

TXT all relative settings can be saved successfully.


Step 9

Reset system and boot to BIOS setup. Verify TXT settings all enabled.

@EB

TXT all relative settings all enabled after reset.


Step 10
Go to Tboot OS@EB

Enter into trusted OS  (If not specified OS, default is Redhat, and redhat OS version will update based on BKC )

Step 11
In tboot OS and run "txt-stat"

@EB

TXT measured launch: FALSE 

secrets flag set: FALSE
